{{Infobox writer |name = Jesse Bowman Bruchac |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{birth-date and age|1972}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |nationality = |citizenship = |notableworks = |education = B.A., Goddard College |occupation = Film Dialect/Dialogue Coach, Translator, Writer, Musician, MMA instructor |period = |genre = |spouse = |children = Carolyn Bruchac, Jacob Bruchac |awards = |signature = |signature_alt = |website = {{URL|westernabenaki.com}} }}
'''Jesse Bowman Bruchac''' (born 1972) is a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] author and language teacher from the [[Abenaki]] tribe.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Senier|first1=Siobhan|title=Dawnland Voices|date=2014|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0-8032-4686-7}}</ref><ref name="Saratoga">{{cite web|title=Jesse Bruchac|url=http://saratogaiku.com/jessebruchac.html|website=Saratoga Kyokushin|publisher=Saratoga Kyokushin LLC}}</ref> He has dedicated much of his life to studying the [[Abenaki language]] and preserving the Abenaki culture. Jesse has also worked extensively with, and taught other Eastern Algonquian languages including the Lenni Lenape, Unkechaug, Shinnecock, Penobscot, Maliseet, Passamaquoddy, Mohegan, Munsee and Unami. He is webmaster of WesternAbenaki.com a free online language learning portal. He has worked as composer for the operetta The Purchase of Manhattan (2015), a translator for the AMC hit show TURN (2014), a short film by Alanis Obomsawin When All the Leaves Are Gone (2010) and as translator, dialect/dialogue coach and composer for the National Geographic movie Saints & Strangers (2015), a film which includes over an hour of translated dialogue in the Western Abenaki language and two months of on set actor training and filming in South Africa with over two dozen actors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saratoga Native Festival Featured Presenters|url=http://www.ndakinnacenter.org/pages/about-us/presenters.php|website=The Ndakinna Education Center|publisher=The Ndakinna Education Center}}</ref> He has travelled throughout the United States teaching both the Abenaki language and culture.<ref name="Hartwick"/> Abenaki scholar Frederick Matthew Wiseman, author of ''The Voice of the Dawn'', calls him an "important contributor to the Abenaki Renaissance."<ref name=voiceofthedawn>{{cite book|last1=Wiseman|first1=Frederick|title=The Voice of the Dawn|date=2001|publisher=UPNE|isbn=9781584650591|edition=illustrated}}</ref> He created the first Abenaki language website.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rockefeller Philanthropy Advisors|title=The Dawnland Singers—Gwsintow8ganal [Honor Songs]|url=http://www.nyfolklore.org/tradarts/music/reviews/dawnland.html|website=New York Folklore Society}}</ref> When he is not traveling, he works as the treasurer for The Ndakinna Education Center and teaches wilderness survival classes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ndakinna Executive Officers and Board Members|url=http://www.ndakinnacenter.org/pages/about-us/staff.php|website=The Ndakinna Education Center}}</ref> He also is an active martial artist, skilled in [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]], [[isshin-ryū]], [[pentjak silat]], and [[taekwondo]].<ref name="Saratoga"/>
== Life and education == Bruchac was born to [[Joseph Bruchac]] and Carol Bruchac. He attended [[Saratoga Springs High School]].<ref name="Saratoga"/> He studied at [[Goddard College]] in Plainfield, VT, where he was primarily interested in creating a syllabus for teaching the Abenaki language. Since then, Jesse has dedicated his life to the preservation and revitalization of the Abenaki language and culture.<ref name=Hartwick>{{cite web|title=Biographies of Native Americans Presenting At Native Balance|url=http://www.hartwick.edu/academics/special-opportunities/annual-academic-theme/balance/native-balance/presenter-biographies|website=Hartwick College}}</ref> In ''The Language of Basketmaking'', Bruchac particularly focuses on revitalizing important writers such as [[Henry Lorne Masta]] and [[Joseph Laurent]].<ref name="Basket">{{cite book|last1=Bruchac|first1=Jesse|title=L8dwaw8gan wji Abaznodakaw8gan: The Language of Basketmaking|date=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0557632107}}</ref> He began teaching conversational Abenaki first at the high school level, and then through the Abenaki Tribal Museum and Cultural Center, until he moved onto other projects in 1999.<ref name="voiceofthedawn" />
Bruchac lives in his hometown [[Greenfield Center]], New York with his two children, Carolyn Bruchac and Jacob Bruchac.<ref name="Basket"/>
==Martial arts== Bruchac began wrestling at the age of 6. In 1990 he became the team captain and the New York State Class A champion for the Suburban Council Championship team, and was awarded the Steve Rue Memorial Award. As an adult he has competed in six different [[North American Grappling Association]] championships. From these he brought home four gold medals and two silver medals. He has also competed as a part of the [[International Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu Federation]], and from these tournaments has brought home five gold medals.<ref name="Saratoga"/> Jesse co-founded Western New York Mixed Martial Arts (WNYMMA) which has "thrived and helped produce major BJJ competitors and MMA talent."<ref>{{cite web|title=BRAZILIAN JIU-JITSU|url=http://www.saratogaiku.com/bjj.html|website=Saratoga Kyokushin|publisher=Saratoga Kyokushin LLC}}</ref> In 2011, he joined his brother Jim Bruchac as a martial arts instructor at the Saratoga Kyokushin.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moyer|first1=Sam|title=Saratoga Kyokushin training institution teaching different forms of martial arts|url=http://www.saratogian.com/general-news/20130101/saratoga-kyokushin-training-institution-teaching-different-forms-of-martial-arts|website=Saratogian News|publisher=The Saratogian}}</ref>
==Public appearances == Bruchac appeared in several episodes of a public access television program called ''Story By Story'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Performers on Youtube|url=http://www.storycircleatproctors.org/youtube.shtml|website=Story Circle At Proctors}}</ref> which aired out of [[Proctor's Theater (Schenectady, New York)|Proctor's Theater]]. In 1993, he co-founded a musical group, the Dawnland Singers, with his father Joseph Bruchac, brother James Bruchac, and aunt Marge Bruchac. John Kirk and Ed Lowman are accompanying instrumentalists.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dawnland Singers|url=http://www.nyfolklore.org/tradarts/music/artist/dawnland.html|website=New York Folklore Society}}</ref> The group has performed across the United States, Canada, and Europe; it once opened for [[The Grateful Dead]] at Woodstock 2 in Highgate, VT.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lemoine|first1=Noelle|title=Williams College to Present Abenaki Storytellers|url=https://communications.williams.edu/news-releases/1_9_2015_abenaki/|website=Williams College}}</ref>
In July and August, 2011, Bruchac presented at the Adirondack Center for Writing's Native American Writers Series, which celebrates a diverse set of writers, including but not limited to the Abenaki and [[Mohawk nation|Mohawk]] tribes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Projects |url=http://www.champlainvalleynhp.org/projects.htm |website=Champlain Valley National Heritage Partnership |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419013618/http://www.champlainvalleynhp.org/projects.htm |archivedate=2015-04-19 |df= }}</ref>
==Books == * Bruchac, Jesse, Joseph Alfred Elie Joubert, and Jeanne A. Brink. ''L8dwaw8gan Wji Abaznodakaw8gan: The Language of Basket Making.'' Greenfield Center, NY: Bowman, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0557632107}} * Bruchac, Jesse. ''Mosbas and the Magic Flute.'' Greenfield Center, NY: Bowman, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0878861484}} * Bruchac, Jesse. ''The Woman and the Kiwakw.'' N.p.: Lulu.com, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1300657576}} * Bruchac, Joseph, and Jesse Bruchac. ''Nisnol Siboal = Two Rivers: Poems in English and Abenaki.'' Greenfield Center, NY: Bowman, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1257430680}} * Wzôkhilain, Pial, and Jesse Bruchac. ''[[Bible translations into Native American languages#Abenaki|The Gospel of Mark Translated into the Abenaki Indian, English and French Languages]].'' N.p.: Lulu.com, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1105197055}}
