{{Infobox scholar | name = Juliet Mitchell | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|size=100%}} | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | fullname = | othernames = | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1940|10|4}} | birth_place = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | era = | region = | nationality = British | alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[St Anne's College, Oxford]] * [[Jesus College, Cambridge]] * [[University College London]] }} | workplaces = Psychoanalysis Unit of [[University College London|University College London (UCL)]] | school_tradition = | main_interests = {{Plainlist| * [[Psychoanalysis]] * [[gender studies]] * [[English Literature]] * [[socialist feminism]] }} | principal_ideas = | major_works = | spouse = {{unbulleted list | {{marriage|[[Perry Anderson]]|7 July 1962|1972|end=div}}| {{marriage|Martin Rossdale|1975|1988|end=div}} | {{marriage|[[Jack Goody]]|2000}}}} | children = Polly Rossdale | parents = | awards = | influences = | influenced = | footnotes = }} '''Juliet Mitchell''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (born 1940) is a British [[professor]], [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]], [[Socialist feminism|socialist feminist]] and author.
== Early life and education == Mitchell was born in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, in 1940, and then moved to England in 1944, where she stayed with her grandparents in the midlands. She attended [[St Anne's College, Oxford]], where she received a degree in English in 1962, as well as doing [[postgraduate]] work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alanmacfarlane.com/DO/filmshow/mitchell1tx_off.htm |title=Juliet Mitchell interviewed by Alan Macfarlane 6th May 2008 |publisher=Alanmacfarlane.com |date=2008-05-06 |accessdate=2018-03-01}}</ref> She taught [[English literature]] from 1962 to 1970 at [[Leeds University]] and [[Reading University]]. Throughout the 1960s, Mitchell was active in [[leftist]] [[politics]], and was on the editorial committee of the journal, ''[[New Left Review]]''.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Juliet Mitchell 1940–|last1=Benewick |first1= Robert | last2 = Green | first2 = Philip |title=The Routledge dictionary of twentieth-century political thinkers |publisher= Psychology Press|year=1998|isbn=9780415096232|page=228 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-jnaCUyzjMQC&pg=PA228}}</ref>
== Career == === ''Women: The Longest Revolution''=== Mitchell gained instant media attention with her pathbreaking article “[http://platypus1917.org/wp-content/uploads/archive/rgroups/2008-chicago/mitchelljuliet_womenlongestrevolution_nlr40.pdf Women: The Longest Revolution]", in the ''[[New Left Review]]'' (1966), an original synthesis of [[Simone de Beauvoir]], [[Frederich Engels]], [[Viola Klein]], [[Betty Friedan]] and other analysts of women's oppression.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juliet Mitchell |url=https://newleftreview.org/I/40/juliet-mitchell-women-the-longest-revolution |title=Juliet Mitchell: Women: The Longest Revolution. New Left Review I/40, November-December 1966 |publisher=Newleftreview.org |date= |accessdate=2018-03-01}}</ref><ref>https://platypus1917.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/38-Singh-Mitchell1.pdf</ref>
=== The Cambridge University Centre for Gender Studies === She is a fellow professor of Psychoanalysis at the [[Jesus College, Cambridge]] and founded the Centre for Gender Studies at [[Cambridge University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jesus.cam.ac.uk/people/professor-juliet-c-w-mitchell |title=Professor Juliet Mitchell &#124; Jesus College in the University of Cambridge |publisher=Jesus.cam.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-03-01}}</ref> In 2010 she is appointed director of the Expanded Doctoral School in Psychoanalytic Studies at the Psychoanalysis Unit of [[University College London]] (UCL).<ref>[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/psychoanalysis/unit-staff/juliet.htm UCL: Juliet Mitchell] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102125301/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/psychoanalysis/unit-staff/juliet.htm |date=2012-11-02 }}</ref>
She is a retired registrant of the [[British Psychoanalytic Council]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}
=== Psychoanalysis and Feminism ===
Mitchell is best known for her book ''Psychoanalysis and Feminism: [[Freud]], [[Wilhelm Reich|Reich]], [[R. D. Laing|Laing]] and Women'' (1974),<ref>{{cite book | last = Mitchell | first = Juliet | title = Psychoanalysis and feminism: Freud, Reich, Laing, and women | publisher = Pantheon Books | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 9780394474724 }}</ref> in which she tried to reconcile [[psychoanalysis]] and [[feminism]] at a time when many considered them incompatible.<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/glossary/people/m/i.htm#mitchell-juliet Juliet Mitchell Archive at marxists.org]</ref> [[Peter Gay]] considered it "the most rewarding and responsible contribution"<ref>{{cite book | last = Gay | first = Peter | author-link = Peter Gay | title = Freud: a life for our time | publisher = Dent | location = London | page = 774 | year = 1988 | isbn = 9780460047616 }}</ref> to the feminist debate on [[Freud]], both acknowledging and rising beyond Freud's [[male chauvinism]] in its analysis. Mitchell saw Freud's asymmetrical view of masculinity and femininity as reflecting the realities of [[Patriarchy|patriarchal culture]], and sought to use his critique of femininity to critique patriarchy itself.<ref>{{cite book | last = Herik | first = Judith | title = Freud on femininity and faith | publisher = University of California Press | location = Berkeley | year = 1985 | page = 15 | isbn = 9780520053335 }}</ref> By insisting on the utility of Freud (particularly in a [[Lacan|Lacanian]] reading) for feminism, she opened the way for further critical work on psychoanalysis and gender.<ref>{{cite book | last = Tandon | first = Neeru | title = Feminism: a paradigm shift | publisher = Atlantic Publishers & Distributors | location = New Delhi | year = 2008 | page = 83 | isbn = 9788126908882 }}</ref>She was an Andrew Dickson White Professor-at-Large at Cornell University from 1993 to 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adwhiteprofessors.cornell.edu/all-professors-at-large-1965-to-june-30-20222/|title=All Professors at Large, 1965-2023|last=Dietrich|first=Penny|date=2018|website=Program for Andrew D. White Professors at Large|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref>
=== Child-rearing === A substantial part of the thesis of the book is that [[Marxism]] may provide a model within which non-[[patriarchy|patriarchal]] structures for rearing children could occur.<ref>{{Citation | last = Mitchell | first = Juliet | contribution = The Oedipus Complex and the patriarchal society | editor-last = Mitchell | editor-first = Juliet | title = Psychoanalysis and feminism: a radical reassessment of Freudian psychoanalysis | pages = 377–381 | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York City | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780465046089 | quote = Under capitalism, the mass of mankind, propertyless and working socially together ''en masse'' for the first time in the history of civilization would be unlikely, ''were it not for the preservation of the family''... }}</ref> The lack of the 'family romance' would remove the [[Oedipus complex]] from a child's development, thus liberating women from the consequences of [[penis envy]] and the feeling of being [[Castration|castrated]] which Mitchell contends is the root cause of women's acceptance that they are inferior.<ref>{{Citation | last = Mitchell | first = Juliet | contribution = The castration complex and penis-envy | editor-last = Mitchell | editor-first = Juliet | title = Psychoanalysis and feminism: a radical reassessment of Freudian psychoanalysis | pages = 95–100 | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York City | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780465046089 }}</ref> According to Mitchell, children are socialised into appropriate gender roles. Therefore, women grow to be equally socialised into becoming the caretakers of their households.<ref>{{Citation | last = Mitchell | first = Juliet | contribution = Conclusion: The holy family and femininity | editor-last = Mitchell | editor-first = Juliet | title = Psychoanalysis and feminism: a radical reassessment of Freudian psychoanalysis | pages = 364–416 | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York City| year = 2000 | isbn = 9780465046089 }}</ref>
=== Feminine sexuality === In her introduction to [[Jacques Lacan]] on feminine sexuality, Mitchell stresses that "in the Freud that Lacan uses, neither the unconscious nor sexuality...[are] pre-given facts, they are [[Social constructivism|constructions]]; that is, they are objects with histories".<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Mitchell | first1 = Juliet (editor) | last2 = Lacan | first2 = Jacques (author) | last3 = Rose | first3 = Jacqueline (translator and editor) | author-link2 = Jacques Lacan | author-link3 = Jacqueline Rose | title = Feminine sexuality: Jacques Lacan and the école freudienne | publisher = Pantheon Books W.W. Norton | location = New York London | year = 1985 | page = 4 | isbn = 9780393302110 }}</ref>
==Bibliography== === Monographs === * {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Woman's Estate | publisher = Penguin | location = Harmondsworth | year = 1971 | isbn = 9780140214253 }} * {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Psychoanalysis and Feminism: Freud, Reich, Laing, and Women | publisher = Pantheon Books | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 9780394474724 }} ::Reissued as: {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Psychoanalysis and Feminism: A radical reassessment of Freudian psychoanalysis | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York City | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780465046089 }} * {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Women, the Longest Revolution | publisher = Pantheon Books | location = New York City | year = 1984 | isbn = 9780394725741 }} * {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Mad Men and Medusas: Reclaiming Hysteria | publisher = Basic Books | location = New York City | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780465046133 }} * {{cite book | last = | first = | title = Siblings: Sex and Violence | publisher = Polity Press | location = Cambridge, UK Malden, Massachusetts | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780745632216 }}
