{{Infobox person |name = Nick Herbert |image = Nick Herbert (physicist).jpeg |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1936|09|07|mf=yes}} |birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, PA]] |spouse = Betsy Rose Rasumny (deceased 2002) |residence = [[United States]] |citizenship = [[United States]] |ethnicity = |fields = |workplaces = |alma_mater = [[Saint Charles Preparatory School, Ohio|Saint Charles Preparatory School]], [[Ohio State University]], [[Stanford University]] |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |notable_students = |known_for = |awards = |signature = |footnotes = <!-- for any footnotes needed to clarify entries above --> }}
'''Nick Herbert''' (born September 7, 1936) is an American physicist and author, best known for his book ''[[Quantum Reality]]''.
==Biography==
Herbert studied [[engineering physics]] at [[Ohio State University]], graduating in 1959. He received a [[Ph.D.]] in physics from [[Stanford University]] in 1967 for work on nuclear scattering experiments. After a one-year teaching job at [[Monmouth College]] in Illinois, Herbert held a number of posts in industry. The most illustrious of these was senior physicist at [[Memorex]] Corporation in [[Santa Clara, California]], where he developed new magnetic materials, as well as magnetic, electrostatic and optical measuring devices, and carried out theoretical work on [[Electron diffraction#Limitations|Lorentz microscopy]]. He was also senior physicist at [[SCM Corporation|Smith-Corona Marchant Corporation]] in Palo Alto, California where he developed a new theory of [[xerographic]] process and worked on early developments in [[ink jet|ink jet printing]].{{sfn|Herbert|2011}}{{sfn|Kaiser|2011|pp=52–54}}
While employed in industry, Herbert was part of the [[Fundamental Fysiks Group]] at [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]], founded in May 1975 by [[Elizabeth Rauscher]] and George Weissmann.<ref>[[David Kaiser|Kaiser, David]]. ''How the Hippies Saved Physics: Science, Counterculture and the Quantum Revival''. W. W. Norton & Company, 2011, pp. xv–xvii, 43ff.</ref> The group's initial interest was in the [[interpretation of quantum mechanics]], the [[EPR paradox]], and [[Bell's inequality]], but members pursued diverse interests that lay outside of mainstream physics, exploring [[psychedelic drugs]], [[psi phenomena]], the nature of [[consciousness]], and speculative connections of these areas with quantum physics. During the 1970s and 1980s, Herbert and Saul-Paul Sirag organized a yearly [[Esalen Institute|Esalen]] Seminar on the Nature of Reality, bringing together participants to discuss the interpretation of quantum mechanics.{{sfn|Kaiser|2011|p=116}} With Richard Shoup of [[Xerox PARC]], Herbert constructed a "Metaphase Typewriter", a "quantum operated" device whose purpose was "to communicate with disembodied spirits".{{sfn|Herbert|2011}} Despite many tests, including an attempt to contact the spirit of [[Harry Houdini]] on the hundredth anniversary of his birth, the group reported no success with the device.{{sfn|Kaiser|2011|p=88}}
Herbert supports a [[holistic]] interpretation of quantum physics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southerncrossreview.org/16/herbert.essay.htm|title=HOLISTIC PHYSICS - OR - AN INTRODUCTION TO QUANTUM TANTRA|website=southerncrossreview.org}}</ref> He has argued for "quantum animism" in which mind permeates the world at every level.<ref>Graham Harvey ''Animism: respecting the living world'' 2005, p. 190</ref> [[Werner Krieglstein]] wrote regarding his quantum animism:
{{cquote|Herbert's quantum animism differs from traditional animism in that it avoids assuming a dualistic model of mind and matter. Traditional dualism assumes that some kind of spirit inhabits a body and makes it move, a ghost in the machine. Herbert's quantum animism presents the idea that every natural system has an inner life, a conscious center, from which it directs and observes its action.<ref>Werner J. Krieglstein ''Compassion: a new philosophy of the other'' 2002, p. 118</ref>}} In 1981, Herbert proposed ''FLASH'', a scheme for sending signals faster than the [[speed of light]] using [[quantum entanglement]].{{sfn|Herbert|1982}} Of this proposal, [[quantum computing]] pioneer [[Asher Peres]] wrote, "I was the referee who approved the publication of Nick Herbert’s ''FLASH paper'', knowing perfectly well that it was wrong. I explain why my decision was the correct one, and I briefly review the progress to which it led." Chief among the results that Peres claimed stemmed from a refutation of Herbert's proposal was the [[no-cloning theorem]], proved by [[William Wootters|Wootters]], [[Wojciech H. Zurek|Zurek]], and [[Dennis Dieks|Dieks]].{{sfn|Peres|2003}}
==Books== *''[[Quantum Reality|Quantum Reality: Beyond the New Physics]]''. New York: Doubleday, 1985. *''Faster Than Light: Superluminal Loopholes in Physics''. New York: Dutton, 1988. *''Elemental Mind: Human Consciousness & the New Physics''. New York: Dutton, 1995. *''Alice Zwischen Den Welten'' (with Bill Shanley). DVA, 1999.
